            <div type="article">
                <div type="section" xml:id="EFT-KB-PALI-CANON-PARALLELS-FRAGMENTS-IN-KANGYUR-article-1">
                    <head type="section" tid="6">Ānāpānassati-sutta : </head>
                    <list type="bullet">
                        <item>
                            <p tid="7">1) The 16 aspects of mindfulness of breathing are found in full in <title xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">don rnam par nges pa</title>  / <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Arthaviniscaya</title> (Toh 317), Degé vol. 72 (mdo sde, sa), folio 182.a-182.b</p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="8">2) Mention in Chapter on Medicines, Degé vol. 2 (‘dul ba, ga), folio 62.b</p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="9">3) And in Prajñāpāramitā in 18,000 Lines (khrid brgyad stong pa, ga) folio 156.a</p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="10">4) In Toh 558, Destroyer of the Great Trichiliocosm, the term “the sixteen recollections of inhaling and exhaling the breath” (<foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn" type="term">dbugs dbyung ba dang rngub pa rjes su dran pa rnam pa bcu drug</foreign>, Skt. <foreign xml:lang="Sa-Ltn" type="term">ṣoḍaśākāra
                                    anāyānānusmṛtiḥ</foreign>) is mentioned as one of the qualities subsumed in that dhāraṇī (see <ref target="https://read.84000-translate.org/translation/UT22084-090-002.html#UT22084-090-002-257">1.247</ref>).</p>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="EFT-KB-PALI-CANON-PARALLELS-FRAGMENTS-IN-KANGYUR-article-2">
                    <head type="section" tid="11">Ratana-sutta</head>
                    <p tid="12">In Toh 558, <title xml:lang="en">Destroyer of the Great Trichiliocosm</title>, <ref target="https://read.84000-translate.org/translation/UT22084-090-002.html#UT22084-090-002-259">1.249</ref> et seq., also found as the main set of verses in the standalone
                        extract Toh 813 / 1098.</p>
                    <p tid="13">The verses are very similar to a set found in the Skt. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Mahāvastu</title> ch. 29.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="section" xml:id="EFT-KB-PALI-CANON-PARALLELS-FRAGMENTS-IN-KANGYUR-article-3">
                    <head type="section" tid="14">Skilling, Peter. “Theravadin Literature in Tibetan Translation.” Journal of the Pali Text Society, vol. XIX, 1993, pp. 69-201. </head>
                    <p tid="15">Toh 31-43 are the thirteen “newly translated texts” (<foreign xml:lang="Bo-Ltn">gsar ’gyur</foreign>), translations almost certainly made from the Pali by a Sri
                        Lankan monk, Ānanandaśrī, who visited Tharpaling in the 14th century, i.e. they are themselves texts of the Theravadin tradition:
                    </p>
                    <list type="bullet">
                        <item>
                            <p tid="16">1. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Dharmacakrapravartana-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="17">2. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Jātaka-nidāna</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="18">3. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Āṭānāṭiya-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="19">4. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Mahāsamaya-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="20">5. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Maitrī-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="21">6. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Maitrībhāvanā-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="22">7. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Pañcaśikṣānuśaṃsa-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="23">8. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Giri-ānanda-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="24">9. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Nandopanandanāgarājadamana-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="25">10. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Mahākāśyapa-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="26">11. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Sūrya-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="27">12. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Candra-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="28">13. <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Mahāmaṅgala-sūtra</title>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <p tid="29">◯ <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Ārya-maitrī-sūtra-nāma</title> (only in Berlin, Lhasa, Narthang, and Peking)</p>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                    <p tid="30">Toh 360 is a chapter (3) of the <title xml:lang="Sa-Ltn">Vimuttimagga</title>. bcom ldan ral gris lists it as translated from Khotanese.</p>
                    <p tid="31">Skilling also lists Tengyur texts</p>
                </div>
            </div>
